    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-05-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-05-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="233" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <head>No. 233.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Baxter</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Fish</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of
                                        the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Tegucigalpa,
                                        Honduras</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-05-30">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 30, 1872</date>.
                                (Received July 3.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 52.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: To-day the official report is received in
                            Tegucigalpa that on the 27th President Medina attacked Comayagua with
                            the hope to repossess <pb facs="0400" n="304" xml:id="pg_304"/> the
                            capital, and that after a battle of many hours he was repulsed with
                            severe loss in killed and wounded, and was forced to retire very much
                            disorganized. This news gives the revolutionists great encouragement for
                            the speedy downfall of President Medina’s government, and the permanent
                            establishment of the provisional government. No information whatever has
                            thus far been received here of the allied armies of Salvador and
                            Guatemala <hi rend="italic">supposed</hi> to be in the field, or of <hi rend="italic">either</hi> of them, except this division.* * * * *
                            *</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>HENRY BAXTER.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
